
Google Grants is a donation program that distributes free in-kind advertising to select 501(c)(3) non profit organizations. Participating non profit organizations are eligible to receive up to $10,000 per month [tpl]cite web|title=Google Grants Program Guidelines and Details | url=http://www.google.com/grants/details.html|work=Google Grants Program Guidelines and Details|accessdate=23 March 2011[/tpl]  in in-kind advertising within the Google AdWords search engine marketing platform. As of June 2010, Google has awarded over $600 million[tpl]cite web|title=Google Grants for Nonprofits|last=Peabody|first=John|url=http://www.commonsensenms.com/2011/03/google-grants-for-nonprofits/|work=Google Grants for Non Profits|accessdate=23 March 2011[/tpl] in grant money to non profit organizations.

== Eligibility ==

Google specifies a number of organizational criteria in order to be eligible for a Google Grant, including:
* Participation in the Google for Nonprofits program
* Current 501(c)(3) status
* Organization website to which you can link your ads

== Application and Management ==

Eligible non profit organizations can apply for a Google Grant online.[tpl]cite web|title=New to Google Grants?|url=http://www.google.com/grants/new/index.html|work=New to Google Grants?|accessdate=23 March 2011[/tpl] The application process can take up to 6 months and is administered by the Google for Nonprofits team. Upon receipt of a Google Grant the grantee is responsible for setting up and managing their Google Grant AdWords account, including its various campaigns, ad groups, ads and keywords. Most Google Grant recipients choose to manage their grant independently, while others seek search engine marketing consultants to optimize their grant performance.

